{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_queenofspades_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280608725/1958030701/0549.xml":{"full_text":"Feature Page\nLAW IN THE NEWS\nMeans Considered\nTo Junk 'Junk' Mail\nBy PHIL YEAGER and\nJOHN STARK\nSpecial Writer* tor Tlx Star\nJunk mail bothers a lot of\npeople, including the postman.\nBut there doesn\u2019t seem to be\na whole lot most of us can do\nabout it except to reject the\njunk daily as it is delivered, or\nwrite our Congressman.\n\u201cJunk mail\u201d is the term given\nto the tons of advertising which\nshow up in your mailbox, espe\ncially the \u201coccupant\u201d mail which\ndoes not even make the pre\ntense of knowing who you are.\nbut is simply mailed to the\noccupant at the address where\nyou happen to be.\nNot long ago a Washington,\nD. C.. substitute mailman,\nHarry E. Beard, got fed up\nwith all the \"junk\u201d he was ex\npected to deliver, so he dumped\n200 pieces of it in the Potomac\nRiver. Unfortunately for Mr.\nBeard, a Harbor Patrol boat\nhappened to be going by and\ncaught him. He was arraigned\non charges of destroying the\nmails.\nDefendant Had Sympathy\nIt is safe to say, though, that\nMr. Beard was one of the most\nsympathetically viewed de\nfendants ever to appear in\ncourt\u2014at least in the eyes of\njunk mail recipients.\nIf you don\u2019t want to receive\nmail of this kind, what can you\ndo about it?\nPostal regulations say that\nDealing With a 'Tortuous' Heart\nDear Dr. Steinerohn: I read\nTour column in yesterday'a\nnewspaper pertaininr to An\ngina Pectoris. I\u2019ve had angina\nfor 18 years. I only get chest\npains when I cook a big meal\nand clean house on the same\ndsgr. My doctor says that my\nheart is tortuous. What does\nthat mean? My son is a sur\ngeon in the Army Air Force\nand in command of a hospital\nIn Germany. 1 don\u2019t want to\nask him because I don't want\nhim to worry about my ail-\nments. And I don't want to\nask my doctor, who never\ncharges me for treatments or\ncalls, because I don\u2019t want\nto impose on him.\n1 am 70 years old. Other\nwise I feel fine except for\narthritis in my knees at times.\nAspirin takes good care of\nthat. Thank you\u2014Mrs. M.M.\nThe term \u201ctortuous\u201d in rela\ntion to the heart usually means\nthat the large artery called the\n\u201caorta\u201d has become elongated.\nIt has lost its elasticity due to\narteriosclerosis. If your heart\nIs not enlarged, a tortuous aorta\n$t 70 does not, in itself, indicate\nundue trouble or danger.\nThe most important part of\ntreatment for your condition\nis to plan your day so that you\ndo not overload your heart.\nFor example, cook the \"big\nmeal\u201d on one day; clean your\nhouse on the next. And put the\nword \"tortuous\u201d out of your\nmind. In looking at x-rays of\nthe heart and doing fluoroscopic\nexaminations over the years, I\nrecall few\u2014if any\u2014persons over\n70 who didn\u2019t have the con\ndition.\nDear Dr. Steinerohn: I\u00ab it\npossible to go through life\nwithout having a headache?\nI don\u2019t know any person I\u2019ve\never talked to who hadn\u2019t\nhad a headache at one time\nor other.\u2014Mr. V. G.\nI have the following letter\nfrom Miami, Fla.:\nFAMOUS FABLES\nBy E. E. EDGAR\nSURRENDER: A society ma\ntrone noted for her wearisome\nparties was trying to snare\nhumorist Oliver Herford as a\ndinner guest.\n\"Will you come Monday\nnight?\u201d she asked him.\n\u201cI can\u2019t.\u201d pleaded Herford.\n\u201cI must finish some illustra\ntions for a magazine.\u201d\n\"Let\u2019s make it Tuesday,\u201d she\nsuggested.\n\"No, not Tuesday. I have an\nappointment with my pub\nlisher.\u201d\n\u201cThen why not make it\nWednesday?\u201d she persisted.\n\u201cNo. I have tickets for the\ntheater.\u201d\n\u201cI do not discourage easily,\nMr. Herford,\u201d she warned him.\n\"How about Thursday?\u201d\n\u201cOh, well,\" sighed Herford.\n\"Let's make it Monday.\u201d\nCONTRIBUTION: Financier\nRussell Sage usually thought\ntwice before parting with\nmoney. At one time, there was\na drive on for a new hospital.\nOne of the members of the\nfund raising committee had re\nceived contributions from a\nnumber of prominent persons.\nListed among the contribu\ntors was \u201cMrs. Russell Sage.\n8100.\" Confident that the pres\nence'of Mrs. Sage's name would\ninspire at least a like contribu\ntion from the financier, the\nsolicitor approached Sage.\nThe latter took one look at\nhis wife\u2019s name and reached\nfor his pen. The other's eyes\nlit up in anticipation of a\ncheck. But the checkbook did\nnot follow. Without a word.\nSage wrote \"Mr.\u201d before his\nwife\u2019s name and handed back\nths list. 1\nmall refused by the addressee\nshall be returned to central\noffices for disposition. So if\nyou meet the mailman at your\nmailbox each day and decline\nto accept the \u201cjunk,\u201d you don\u2019t\nhave to take it. But this would\nbe a hardship on both the mail\nman and you, so there seems\nlittle point in it. Also, you can\nstop delivery of all mail if you\nchoose; but you cannot very\nwell ask the post office depart\nment to sort through mail ad\ndressed to you and weed out\nwhat you don\u2019t want.\nCongress Could Act\nPerhaps the most effective\nidea would be to organise\nenough pressure against junk\nmail to get Congress to do\nsomething about it.\nCongress has pretty broad\npowers under the Constitution\nto protect the mails, prevent\nharmful use of postal facilities\nand exclude certain types of\ncommunications. Whether it\ncould regulate junk mail in\nsuch away as to substantially\nreduce its output or eliminate;\nit entirely may be a nice legal\nquestion.\nBut, particularly in view of\nthe current postal deficits, it\nmay yet be tried, at least to\nthe extent of Jacking up rates\non certain mall advertising\nschemes.\nSunday: Parents, children and the\nlaw.\nHow to\nSTOP KILLING\nYOURSELF\nBy DR. PETER J. STEINCROHN\n\u201cDr. Steincrohn, in one of\nlyour columns that appeared in\nthe paper in Asheville. N. C.,\nyou gave an account of a \"most\nremarkable man.\u201d It was about\na 50-year-old man who never\nhad a headache\n\u201cI am writing this to say that\nI am past 90, and have never\nhad such a thing as a head\nache. and have never had any\nillness, aside from those that\nare incidental to childhood.\nMoreover, I never have oc\ncasion to take anything in the\nnature of a laxative. I consider\nthis a fairly good record, and\nought to qualify me for the\n\u201cremarkable class.\u2019! i Sincerely,\nG. E. W.\u2019V\nDear Dr. Steincrohn: My\nhusband, who is 62. has gut\ntered what the doctor calls\na cerebral thrombosis. Will\nyen explain what it is? Thank\nyou. Mrs. N.\"C.\nThe underlying process is\nsimilar to that found in coro\nnary artery disease. It is called\natherosclerosis. This, in turn,\nis due to faulty cholesterol\nmetabolism that narrows the\nlumen of the arteries. When\nthat happens in a blood vessel\nin the brain we call it cerebral\nthrombosis\u2014if it has completely\nclosed off the artery.\nIf the artery affected is quite\nsmall, there may be few symp\ntoms; sometimes only head\nache or a dizzy spell. If the\nartery is large in a vital area,\nthe patient may have paralysis\nof arm, leg and speech. Extent\nof recovery will depend upon\nhow much collateral (new) cir\nculation forms.\nSometimes cerebral embolism\n(from a small clot carried In\nthe blood stream) will simulate\nthrombosis. If it is small,\nparalysis and other symptoms\nmay clear up within 24 hours.\nIn cerebral hemorrhage (where\nthe artery has actually rup\ntured) there is unconsciousness,\nfollowed by paralysis that is\nusually permanent.\nTreatment of these \u201ccerebral\naccidents\u201d usually is more suc\ncessful the sooner we can dif\nferentiate one condition from\nthe other.\nReleased bv Th\u00bb Bell Syndicate, Inc.\nTEENS!\nHear Your Favorite Hit Tunes On\nREQUEST TIME\nMonday-Saturday, 9:00 P.M.. 1:00 A.M. BDwPNfcjSB\nw r\nTRUE LIFE ADVENTURES -\u00bbr w.k Di.n.y\nPERIL. IN\nPARADISE. 4\nTThE UNDERWATER\n\n\u00a9EEP CREVICES IN THE CORAL.\nmgKB/fP CONCEAL LURKING DANGERS....\nsuch as the MORAV EEL which\nues in wait for the unwarv.\nJIM BISHOP:\nREPORTER\nStory of How a Friendship Ended\nShe talked. I nodded. We sat\nin the morning sun at the\nPhoenix Stadium and I could\nlisten and still watch Dusty\nRhodes miss two pitches and\nslam the next one through\nsecond so hard that he almost\ntore an inflelder\u2019s arm off. She\nwas pleasant and pretty and\nthe wattles were just beginning\nto show on her neck and the\neyes looked sun-squinted even\nin the shade.\nShe could talk. She never saw\na play. The hair was dark and\nit lifted slightly every time she\nturned her head. The tone was\nsincere and she told me how\noften she went to church. She\nhad been married once, but it\nwas all over. Men are no good, I\neven the best of them. Her slim\ncurving brows were about five\nfeet from the spiked heels.\nBetween them was a size 10\ndress and two strands of choker\npearls.\nWillie Mays leaned against\nthe batter\u2019s cage and said, \u201cI\ngotta hit. Somebody gotta let\nme hit,\u201d and Hank Sauer said,\n\u201cWell, get in there and hit.\u201d\nHer trouble, she said, was that\nshe was too good-hearted. A\nsoft touch. The hands were\nlong and bony and the blue\nveins made little forks in the\nskin. If she hadn\u2019t been so good\nto everybody, she wouldn\u2019t be\nsuch a nervous wreck now.\nAn Easy Mark\nEverybody took advantage of\nher. Take Dot. Dot had been\nher girl friend for oh, maybe\n15 years. They had more on\neach other than a pair of bank\nrobbers. Dot, she told me, was\na wonderful girl. She had looks\nand figure and she came from\na fine family. But drink?\nBrother. You know how mixed\nup a girl can get when she\u2019s\nconfused.\nDot was bom confused. She\nliked men but the men she\nliked alwavs turned out to be\nmarried three months l\u00dfter.\nThen she would start drinking\nand it was un to Miss Wattles\nto wring her out. Goodhearted?\nToo much so. she said, if vou\ndon\u2019t mind mP saying it. One\ntime I gave her *BO because\nthe bank threatened to throw\nher in jail for writing checks.\nAnother time she wanted to\nmove out of a hotel but they\nheld her luggage until Miss\nWattles gave her $l2O. Always\na touch. Always a desperate\ntouch. And always Dot said\nthat she was about to begin a\nnew life.\nThe kid, Peter Burnside, was\npitching and he had that nice\neven poetry of the arm. and the\nball came in like a blur. The j\nbatter swung and you could\nhear the bullwhip snap as the\nball smashed into the catcher\u2019s\nmitt. It was like trying to hit\na butterfly with a club.\nThis new life routine almost\ndrove Miss Wattles crazy, she\nsaid. Over the years. Dot fell\ninto her arms many times, al\nways weeping, always promis\nJigpi mm\nm* 'WE\ning, always borrowing money,\nalways meeting a new man. She\nasked me if she was boring me,\nand, without looking away from\nBurnside, I said no. She talked\non and on, pulling the hem\ndown a half inch, fingering the\nwatch, wringing the hands,\nblushing away an imaginary\nfleck of hair.\nThe last time Dot asked for\nSSO. Miss Wattles gave it and\nsaid it was final. Dot said I\u2019m\nno good Miss Wattles said oh\nyes you are, you\u2019re going to\nstart a new life. The tears came\nto Dot\u2019s eyes and she said I\nwill, I will. This I will.\nRigney walked up and down\nthe baseline with his hands in\nhis back pockets, head thrust\nforward, Adam s apple bobbing\nas he watched the men of the\nSan Francisco Giants. He be\nlieves in them. He has got to\nmake them believe in them\nselves.\nA Final Note\nMiss Wattles lowered her\nvoice a little I was so surprised\nthat I turned to look at her.\nThe words were still tumbling\nfast, but the tone was low and\nthe lips kept peeling away from\nthe snowy teeth. Dot went out\nand blew the SSO on a new\ndress. Miss Wattles heard about\nit and became angry.\nShe phoned Dot just to let\na Shapiro Soys:\n11 Happier\nIWB\nv Replace with Matchless\nPemaglas\n7he Original\nfnm glass\nF I LINED\n1 Gas Automatic\nI Water Heoter\nbjMopy\nInstallation I*- i\nr\u20144o Gal 10 YEAR GUAR.\u2014t\nLOW\nI\" 5 \u201cJ\n1 NO MONEY DOWN\u2014\u2014I\nPay on Year Gas Bill\nShapiro\n3006 Georgia Avenue N W\nColl TU. 2-1900\nFAMILY COUNCIL\nShe Shuns\nChildren's\nHome Offer\nTHE PROBLEM\nSHIRLEY E.\u2014Mother should\ncome and stay with us.\n11 MRS. D. G.\u2014lt\u2019s silly, but I\ncan\u2019t part with the house.\nTHE DETAILS\nShirley E.\u2014 My sister and\nbrother and I are deeply con\ncerned about our mother, who\nbecame a widow more than six\nmonths ago.\nWe are all married and have\nnice homes and are very eager\nto have Mother come and stay\nwith us. She could live with\nany one of us, or change\naround, as she pleases.\nInstead, she has been living\nin the old house and brooding\nover the past. The house was\nmuch too big for her, even\nher know that she knew. \u201cYou\ni and your new life,\u201d she said.\n\u201cWell, I hope the dress does\nyou a lot of good. Wear it in\nhealth, kid. Just don\u2019t bother\nme any more, no matter what\nhappens. From now on, you\u2019re\non your own.\u201d\nMiss Wattles went to bed in\ngood conscience. She was a\ngood woman. A faint flush of\npink stood over the Supersti\ntion Mountains when the police\ntapped on the door. Did she\nj know Dot? Yes she did. Well,\nthe cops said, Dot had just\nkilled herself and had left a\n1 note for Miss Wattles.\nShe opened it and the hands\nshook. \u201cI told ypu,\u201d it said.\n\u201cthat I could start a new life.\u201d\nA man in the stands held a\nmovie camera. \u201cHere, Willie,\u201d\nlhe called. \u201cWillie, Willie.\u201d\nI Willie Mays paid no attention.\nHe dropped into the dugout and\ndisappeared.\nCopyrlcht. IB6R. Klnc Features\nSyndicate. Inc.\nr\nMonday: The Army coptain nobody\nwanted.\nCAP'N TUGG and \"POPEYE\"6:3O\njSS Live, Plus Cartoons; It's \"See-Worthy\" S\nBUCKSKINS JAMBOREE 7:00\nSmooth Western ond Popular Music\nil| Featuring Song Stylist Alice Sharon\nBADGE 714 7:30\nfH Authentic Stories From Los Angeles\nj\u00a3| Police Files\nFEATURE FILM 8:00\n\"Flamingo Road\", Joan Crawford\nfn and David Brian\nWHIRLYBIRDS 9:30\nqjjf Adventure in the Air; Chopper\" R\n|ip: Drama J\u00a7|\nWATERFRONT 10:00\nf\u00a7S Action on the San Francisco B\n||l Waterfront\"\nIF YOU HAD A MILLION 10:30\nI 11 O'CLOCK MOVIE 11:00\nPp \"Wagon Master\"; Excitnig Western\nmm (Matthew Warren and the News) Hg\n1 11:00\n(Barbara Harris and the Weather)\nItBPSi\nCHANNEL\nTODAY \u2014Top Price for Your\noqcio\nColonial Petr says:\nYou\u2019ve GOT it We NEED it\nI\u2019ll Trade New Money For Old Junk!\nWe 'u v JS I Copper, Brass, Lead, Alu-\nWisconsin Avenue minum. Batteries, Scrap\nbetween M and K Iron, Cast Iron, Rags, Mag\nstreets N.W., in azines. Newspapers,\nthe heart of Old\nGeorcetown. Closest She, te Virginia\nf] OLONIAL\nCOMPANY\nCleanest Junk Yard in Town \u2014FE. 3*2800\n1*11,0,0c. Street, N.W Open Saturdays Until 4\nvtf' t fill to ui tettk confidence\u2014our scaled I\nore government inspected and I I\nijlM}iiiiiiiiTh>-<rrtiiiiiiiiiillll\nI I\nNew Jersey Ave. end lye St S.E. Lincoln 7-5178 S\nRIVER ROAD IRON fr METAL CO. fl\nKenilworth end Lewrence St. APpleten 7-0400\nBladensbury. Md.\nwhen Dad was alive. A good\npart of it is just closed off.\nWhat is the sense of her\nbeing so lonely in that big,\nempty house?\nMrs. D. G.\u2014l know it\u2019s silly,\nbut I have lived in that house\nnerly 40 years and I can\u2019t quite\nbring myself to part with it.\nIt\u2019s true that it is lonely here\nand there are a lot of discom\nforts. Sometimes I can\u2019t get\nThe Family Council consist) at\njudge, a psychiatrist, three clergy\nmen, a newspaper editor, a women's\neditor and two writers. Each artida\nis a summary ot an actual case\nhistory. The council reports on\nproblems that hare been dealt with\nby responsible agencies.\nanyone to do all the necessary\nthings around the house. I know\nthe children think I\u2019m crazy\nwhen I complain about it, but\nI\u2019d rather have the house and\ncomplain than get rid of it.\nThen there are my things.\nI\u2019ve accumulated so many\nthings over the years. The\nchildren don\u2019t think much of\nthem, but I would want to keep\nthem, and then I\u2019d be a\nnuisance.\nTHE COUNCIL\u2019S VIEW\nAll the experts are behind\nyou, Mrs. D. O.! The experience\nof many other widowed women\nhas been that giving up a home\nhas brought considerable grief.\nDespite her children\u2019s wel\ncoming arms, Mrs. D. G. will\nfeel dispossessed when she\nwalks in rooms that are not her\nown among things that arc not\nher own. The \u201cthings\u201d Mrs.\nD. G. has accumulated rep\nresent her tastes, her interests,\nher personality. They are her\nattachment to life.\nEven if her children com\npromise and are willing to\n\u201ctolerate\u201d a part of her collec\ntions, Mrs. D. G. would have\nto cut down her ownership to\nsuit their convenience. Imme\ndiately she Is placed in a sub\nservient position.\nHowever, it is not necessary,\nin this day of housing short\nages, for Mrs. D. G. to be lonely\nin a big house. She should con\nsider renting a portion of her\nhome, preferably to a family.\nTHE EVENING STAR, Washington, D. C.\nraiDAV. MARCH 188*\nShe may And it very profitable\nto charge a moderate rental in\nreturn for some help around\nthe house from the man of the\nfamily.\nThis arrangement will lick a\nvariety of problems income,\nloneliness and upkeep of the\nproperty.\n(Copyriaht 1868. Genersl Features\nCorp.i\nMonday: Wife demands freedom\nto have her own fling.\nOpen 11:30 _ n _ Delicious\nA.M. to Drinks ond\n10:30 W.nes\nWho Know\nEj THE Places Yl\nH rut regularly at lB\nAlfonso's IK\nH Famous for Steaks, Iff!\nBl\\\\ Roost Beef, Chops IB\nmU Select Lenten Dishes f H\nFREE DINNER AD\nVpL\\v\u00abrmont and l Sts. IIE*\n1403 Vff Phono\nL SR. N.W. MI. S-7803\nHOW.. A ttutuHL t&...\nBATHROOM jSWSSM\nOUTFIT\nRe